`.add_resource_default::<R>()` / `.add_column::<T>()` /
`.add_virtual::<V>()` / `.add_kit::<K>()` / `.with_memory(m)` /
`.with_threads(t)` / `.with_clock(c)` call site with the
unified `.with(value)` shape. One PR per consumer repo. Tracked
here so the post-merge follow-up is not lost.

## Round 202605101036 follow-ups

### Heterogeneous-core P/E detection per-OS implementation

Topic 6 axis E ships in v1; the detection code lands in this crate
as a follow-up. The detection surface is per-OS: on x86_64 it reads
CPUID leaf 0x1A via an inline-asm intrinsic, returning a CoreClass
per logical core. On Linux it walks
`/sys/devices/system/cpu/cpuN/topology/cluster_id`, falling back to
cpufreq `scaling_max_freq` thresholding when the cluster_id surface
is absent on pre-6.0 kernels. On macOS it calls
`sysctlbyname("hw.perflevel0.physicalcpu")` for the P-core count and
treats the remaining cores as E-cores, with an IOKit fallback if
sysctl is absent. On Windows it calls `GetSystemCpuSetInformation`,
which returns per-CPU efficiency class directly.

The stub-fallback path returns all-P when detection fails. Tracked
as its own follow-up round so the per-OS work doesn't bloat the
runtime megaround's src CL.

### Tree-barrier follow-up

Topic 6 axis I ships v1 with the centralised atomic counter +
futex-wake-all phase barrier. Tree-barrier (log2(N) fan-in) is a
follow-up if bench evidence at 32+ cores shows measurable cacheline
ping-pong on the centralised counter. Adds `PoolFrame.phase_arrived`
as a flat `[AtomicU32; LOG2_MAX_CORES]` array indexed by tree level.

### Bench-driven follow-ups (round 202605101036 overnight benches)

Twenty-nine benches landed in `mock/benches/` during the 2026-05-11
overnight autonomous run. Findings index lives at
`mock/benches/NIGHT_FINDINGS_2026-05-11.md`. Several findings revise
or refine engine design decisions:

**Plan-stage enum dispatch rule (revised).** The `match_arm_count`
bench surfaced a sharp icache cliff at 64 match arms at N=16384
(+628%). The `fnptr_table_dispatch` follow-up FALSIFIED the proposed
fix of refactoring to fn-pointer table: at 16 variants, fnptr-table
is +56% slower than match at N=1024-4096 due to indirect-call BTB
mispredictions. **Revised rule:** keep hot-loop enum dispatch ≤8
variants in plan-stage code; for larger discriminant spaces, batch
by variant (process all variant-0 records first, then variant-1,
etc.) so one handler stays hot in icache. Stage / Phase /
WorkUnitKind enums currently fit ≤8; design should preserve.

**fold_strategy implications for morsel-loop reductions.** Quad-way
interleaved-accumulator reduction is ~3.8x faster than single-acc
sequential at N=16384 (and LLVM does NOT auto-extract this ILP).
Topic 7 morsel-loop consumers writing `let mut acc` over a column
pay a 2-4x latency tax on mul-heavy reductions. Substrate should
ship an interleaved-accumulator reduction primitive, tracked
upstream as the `arvo::Fold` trait family design round.

**Atomic increment shape validated.** `atomic_inc_strategy` confirms
Topic 6 axis I: `fetch_add(1, Relaxed)` beats CAS-loop by 11-19%
via LSE LDADD on aarch64. The centralised-counter phase-barrier
design over a CAS-loop trait abstraction is empirically correct.
Bench file: `mock/benches/atomic_inc_strategy_n*_findings.md`.

**Per-fiber atomic-metrics cost validated.** `atomic_vs_plain`
confirms Topic 3 M3: `AtomicU64+Relaxed` is free in single-thread
non-contended code on aarch64. AdaptMetrics fields can be
AtomicU64+Relaxed without throughput cost AS LONG AS the per-fiber
cache-line invariant holds (no cross-core contention during hot
loop). Cache-line invariant is the design responsibility; the bench
validates the cost claim.

**Pow2 cap convention validated.** `modulo_strategy` shows pow2 const
modulo is 2.2x faster than non-pow2 and 2.9x faster than runtime-
opaque divisor. Validates every cap-as-const-generic choice in
PoolFrame: MAX_FIBERS, MAX_CORES, MAX_UNITS, MICRO_MORSEL_INTERVAL,
MAX_DRIFT_RECORDS, MAX_PLAN_AFFECTING_RESOURCES.

**Inline strategy.** `inline_strategy` shows LLVM auto-inlines
small leaf fns into hot loops reliably under release+fat-LTO.
Defensive `#[inline]` on per-record morsel step fns is cheap
insurance, not load-bearing.

**Cross-references.** Each bench finding above carries the full
table and design implications in `mock/benches/NIGHT_FINDINGS_2026-05-11.md`.
The synthesis section at the top of that file groups all 29 benches
by design impact category.
